 his, this fifty pence?\nCould he have it?\nCarefully, Charlie pulled it out from under the snow", "516": " It was damp and dirty, but otherwise\nperfect", "517": "\nA WHOLE fifty pence!\nHe held it tightly between his shivering fingers, gazing down at it", "518": " It meant one thing to\nhim at that moment, only one thing", "519": " It meant FOOD", "520": "\nAutomatically, Charlie turned and began moving towards the nearest shop", "521": " It was only ten\npaces away ", "522": " ", "523": " ", "524": " it was a newspaper and stationery shop, the kind that sells almost everything,\nincluding sweets and cigars ", "525": " ", "526": " ", "527": " and what he would do, he whispered quickly to himself ", "528": " ", "529": " ", "530": " he\nwould buy one luscious bar of chocolate and eat it all up, every bit of it, right then and there ", "531": " ", "532": " ", "533": "\nand the rest of the money he would take straight back home and give to his mother", "534": "\n11\nThe Miracle\nCharlie entered the shop and laid the damp fifty pence on the counter", "535": "\n'One Wonka's Whipple-Scrumptious Fudgemallow Delight,' he said, remembering how\nmuch he had loved the one he had on his birthday", "536": "\nThe man behind the counter looked fat and well-fed", "537": " He had big lips and fat cheeks and a\nvery fat neck", "538": " The fat around his neck bulged out all around the top of his collar like a rubber ring", "539": "\nHe turned and reached behind him for the chocolate bar, then he turned back again and handed it\nto Charlie", "540": " Charlie grabbed it and quickly tore off the wrapper and took an enormous bite", "541": " Then\nhe took another ", "542": " ", "543": " ", "544": " and another ", "545": " ", "546": " ", "547": " and oh, the joy of being able to cram large pieces of something\nsweet and solid into one's mouth! The sheer blissful joy of being able to fill one's mouth with rich\nsolid food!\n'You look like you wanted that one, sonny,' the shopkeeper said pl